Project 1 - To do list - 1


We are going to create a project (To do list). Which contains various component.

Creating Component

Generally component contains of 3 files included html for ui, css for styles and ts for logic.

Basic name keeping for file in component - name.component.extension - Eg: header.component.ts

In ts file,

We need to export the class to be used outside the component.

  1. export class HeaderComponent{}


In order to make it as a component we need to import the component from angular/core and decorator @Component.

  1. import {Component} from '@angular/core';

  3. @Component({
  4.     selector: 'app-header',   #This the word we use in project where we need to use this component.
  5.     standalone: true,   #To mention whether its a standalone component or module based component.
  6.     templateUrl: './header.component.html',   #HTML to be used by this component should be mentiond. We can mention file name or we can also type entire                  HTML code for this approach use template instead of templateUrl.
  7. })
  8. export class HeaderComponent{}


We can create header.component.html and add HTML part.

  1. <header>
  2. <h1>Hello World</h1>
  3. </header>


To see this component render need to mention <app-header></app-header> in the index.html.

  1. <!doctype html>
  2. <html lang="en">
  3. <head>
  4.  <meta charset="utf-8">
  5.  <title>HelloWorld</title>
  6.  <base href="/">
  7.  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  8.  <link rel="icon" type="image/x-icon" href="favicon.ico">
  9. </head>
  10. <body>
  11.  <app-header></app-header>
  12.  <app-root></app-root>
  13. </body>
  14. </html>


Generally Angular wont search for component to render in the UI until it is mentioned in main.ts

  1. import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';
  2. import { appConfig } from './app/app.config';
  3. import { AppComponent } from './app/app.component';
  4. import { HeaderComponent } from './app/header.component';

  6. bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, appConfig)
  7.  .catch((err) => console.error(err));

  9. bootstrapApplication(HeaderComponent);


ts files import should be done without the extension (line 3,4)

But its not a best practice to use like this. We need to call only one component which is the root component in this case AppComponent in the bootstrapApplication in main.ts.

But how to render other component? We can call the other components inside the root component.

  1. #ap.,component.html
  2. <app-header></app-header>


It will display app-header is not known element. In this case we need to import the HeaderComponent inside the Appcomponent. How to do it? import the component in app.component.ts and also add it to the imports properties in the @component decorator.

  1. #app.component.ts
  2. import { Component } from '@angular/core';
  3. import { RouterOutlet } from '@angular/router';
  4. import { HeaderComponent } from './header.component';

  6. @Component({
  7.  selector: 'app-root',
  8.  standalone: true,
  9.  imports: [RouterOutlet,HeaderComponent], #this will register the HeaderComponent should be used in AppComponent
  10.  templateUrl: './app.component.html',
  11.  styleUrl: './app.component.css'
  12. })
  13. export class AppComponent {
  14.  title = 'hello-world';
  15. }

Dynamic Data Rendering

There is 2 ways to bind the variables from ts to HTML.

First one is string interpolation. Its using {{}} in HTML file. We can use any public variable from ts to use in html the private variables cant be used in HTML it can be only used in ts file. Example of private variable (private selectedUsers = DUMMY_USERS[randomIndex];)

  1. #user.component.html - string interpolation example
  2. <div>
  3.    <button>
  4.        <img/>
  5.        <span>{{selectedUsers.name}}</span>
  6.    </button>
  7. </div>


Another method is property binding. To show image we can also use string interpolation but its not the best practice. In this case we wrap the element with [ ]. By doing this we can ping the img property to the DOM instead of just printing like a string.

  1. #user.component.html
  2. <div>
  3.    <button>
  4.        <img [src]="'assets/users/' + selectedUsers.avatar" [alt]="selectedUsers.name"/>
  5.        <span>{{selectedUsers.name}}</span>
  6.    </button>
  7. </div>


Getter in typescript

Its not best practice to hardcode in HTML files. So we can use getter from ts file and use it in html. Getter is basically a method that can be used in HTML. Now when using the varible inside the ts class other than in HTML we should use this keyword like js.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2. export class UserComponent {
  3.  selectedUsers = DUMMY_USERS[randomIndex];

  5.  get imagePath(){ //getter method
  6.    return 'assets/users/' + this.selectedUsers.avatar;
  7.  }
  8. }


Now we can use this getter in the HTML file

  1. #user.component.html
  2. <div>
  3.    <button>
  4.        <img [src]="imagePath" [alt]="selectedUsers.name"/> //we can use it without () like a property.
  5.        <span>{{selectedUsers.name}}</span>
  6.    </button>
  7. </div>


Event Binding

We need to listen to the user input and change the UI dynamically.

For example we need to add eventListener say click event to a button to do something when it is clicked. we need to bind the event with ( ). We can call some method from ts file for the evenyListsner to make the code work when the button is clicked.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2. export class UserComponent {
  3.  selectedUsers = DUMMY_USERS[randomIndex];

  5.  get imagePath(){
  6.    return 'assets/users/' + this.selectedUsers.avatar;
  7.  }

  9.  onSelectUser(){ //method used for the click event
  10.    console.log("clicked");
  11.  }
  12. }


  1. #user.component.html
  2. <div>
  3.    <button (click)="onSelectUser()"> //The event is binded to the method.
  4.        <img [src]="imagePath" [alt]="selectedUsers.name"/>
  5.        <span>{{selectedUsers.name}}</span>
  6.    </button>
  7. </div>

 

Managing State

Now lets see click event changing the UI that is changing the state of the webpage.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2.  onSelectUser(){
  3.    const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random()* DUMMY_USERS.length);
  4.    this.selectedUsers = DUMMY_USERS[randomIndex];
  5.  }


Angular js uses a change detection mechanism called zone.js to dynamically update UI based on the events, expired timers, etc.

The above example is one of changing the state in angular which is used in older versions of the angular. There is also a new method for this called signals.

Signals

They are special kind of code to notify angular about any event occurred to change the state respectively.

To use signal we need to import it from the @angular/core. Now we should create a signal by passing a value as an argument and assign it to a variable in the ts file. Signal is basically an object that stores a initial value and notify the templates(HTML) where those values are used to change the state when that value changes.

We can change the signal value by using a set method for the variable.

To use the signal value in the template we should call with ( ). For example if the selectedUsers is changed as signal property in HTML we should not use it as {{selectedUsers.name}} instead we should use it as {{selectedUsers().name}}. So whenever we need to display the property of signal we want to consider it as the method.

So now angular understands it as the signal and subscribe it in the background that is when the value of the signal changes it will re render it in the UI.

When using the signal we dont need get method to return the value to HTML instead we use computed.

The computed method takes a function as argument with arrow function '=>' we return the required value to HTML.

Computed should be used to return the value when it is declared as the signal.

Now when using computed() the angular subscribe it to the signal and it will listen the signal so when the value in signal changes it automatically changes the computed value and UI is rendered accordingly. So using computed is efficient since it wont change the value every time the component changes it will change only when the signal changes.

computed property also should be executed with ( ) in template. Example instead of imagePath we should use imagePath().

Simply the computed is also a signal which changes when the signals it depends on changes.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2. import { Component, computed, signal } from '@angular/core'; //signal and computed is imported
  3. import { DUMMY_USERS } from '../dummy-users';

  5. const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random()* DUMMY_USERS.length); //to get random index from the array to give to the variable

  7. @Component({
  8.  selector: 'app-user',
  9.  standalone: true,
  10.  imports: [],
  11.  templateUrl: './user.component.html',
  12.  styleUrl: './user.component.css'
  13. })
  14. export class UserComponent {
  15.  selectedUsers =signal(DUMMY_USERS[randomIndex]);  //signal is initiated
  16.  imagePath = computed(() => 'assets/users/' + this.selectedUsers().avatar); //computed is used to get the value of signal

  18.  onSelectUser(){
  19.    const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random()* DUMMY_USERS.length);
  20.    this.selectedUsers.set(DUMMY_USERS[randomIndex]); //set a new value to the signal
  21.  }
  22. }


  1. #user.component.html
  2. <div>
  3.    <button (click)="onSelectUser()">
  4.        <img [src]="imagePath()" [alt]="selectedUsers().name"/> //signal and computed is called as method using ()
  5.        <span>{{selectedUsers().name}}</span>
  6.    </button>
  7. </div>

Now we want to pass the value say the id of the user to component from where it is used in HTML. How to do it?

Giving Input To The Component

To set a property like that in the component first we should add @Input( ) decorator to a property that has to be get as input to the component in ts file. Now the property with @Input( ) decorator can be set from outside the component.

Now to pass the input to the component we can go the place where the component is called and pass the input with the property that is marked as input in the ts file. In our case user details should be passed. To do that we need to import DUMMY_USERS into app component and set it in the ts file and should be passed as input to user component.

Now the variable mentioned in user.component.ts with @Input( ) will throw an error because we didnt mentioned the data type of the variable that is to be received from app component. In type scrip we need to mention the data type of the input variables that are received from other components. It is mentioned as @Input() avatar: string; here string is the datatype that are going to be received.

Now it will throw the error that the avatar is not initialized error. In type script we can add '!' to the input to explicitly say we know that the value is not initialized but it will be assigned definitely in this case the value will be set from the app component to user component. For example @Input() avatar !: string;

Now we can add more input like name.

We said previously if we dont use '!' in the input we get error that variable is not initialized but there will be cases we dont pass the value for input from app component. How to handle that?

We need to add configuration option in the @Input decorator like we add in @Component() decorator. We have required configuration option in Input decorator we can set it to false if it is optional.

If I add @Input({required: true}) avatar!: string; but if I dont pass the avatar value from app component to user component I receive a error message in template file.

We can use this to catch and fix the errors during development process itself.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2. export class UserComponent {
  3.  @Input({required:true}) avatar !: string; //required configuration added
  4.  @Input({required:true}) name !: string;
  5.  get imagePath(){
  6.    return 'assets/users/' + this.avatar;
  7.  }
  8.  onSelectUser(){

  10.  }


Using Signals to Accept the Input

We need to import input (with lowercase i) from @angular/core.

Input - decorator

input - function

Example - avatar = input( );

This will tell the angular that the avatar is the input to be used in the component.

We can also assign default value to the input. Example - avatar = input(' ');

We can also explicitly mention datatype to the input in ts. Example - avatar = input<string>( );

We can also use required in this method. - Example - avatar = input.required<string>( ); - we cant pass default value in this because the input is required from other components. 

It doesnt matter whether we use @Input or input() in component we can send value from app component the same way.

Now we use computed( ) to get imagePath and also use ( ) in HTML file to display values.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2. import { Component, computed, input } from '@angular/core'; //imports


  5. @Component({
  6.  selector: 'app-user',
  7.  standalone: true,
  8.  imports: [],
  9.  templateUrl: './user.component.html',
  10.  styleUrl: './user.component.css'
  11. })
  12. export class UserComponent {
  13.  avatar = input.required<string>(); //signal inputs
  14.  name = input.required<string>();
  15.  imagePath = computed(() =>{
  16.    return 'assets/users/' + this.avatar(); //computed image path
  17.  });
  18.  onSelectUser(){

  20.  }
  21. }


  1. #user.component.html
  2. <div>
  3.    <button (click)="onSelectUser()">
  4.        <img [src]="imagePath()" [alt]="name()"/>
  5.        <span>{{name()}}</span>
  6.    </button>
  7. </div>


The input values are only read-only values which will be changed only when the input from component outside that is app component gives different value. So the signals can be set only if it is defined inside the component the input( ) signals is only read-only.

Outputting Data From the Component

We need to output the data from user component to app component. So when the user is clicked the clicked user's data should be outputted to app component ti show their respective tasks.

This can be done with the help of Output property. We need @Output( ) decorator for that.

unlike @Input( ) the output decorator will have initial value which is the instance of the EventEmitter. 

@Output( ) select = new EventEmitter( ). - this EventEmitter will emit the value of select to the parent component.

So When the click is happened it will trigger onSelectUser( ) method inside that we can emit the value of slelected user to the parent component using this.select.emit( ).

Now we can listen to the select event that is emitted from user component in its parent component that is app component.

That can be done using event binding in app component and call a function in its ts file. Need to mention type of the argument in ts file.

Now we need to pass the value emitted from the user component which we get in app component html file. The argument is $event which is emitted in user component. Example - (select)="onSelectUser($event)"

This $event holds the value that is emitted from the user component.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2. import { Component, EventEmitter, Input, Output } from '@angular/core';


  5. @Component({
  6.  selector: 'app-user',
  7.  standalone: true,
  8.  imports: [],
  9.  templateUrl: './user.component.html',
  10.  styleUrl: './user.component.css'
  11. })
  12. export class UserComponent {
  13.  @Input({required:true}) id !: string
  14.  @Input({required:true}) avatar !: string;
  15.  @Input({required:true}) name !: string;

  17.  @Output() select = new EventEmitter(); //Output from the component to parent
  18.  get imagePath(){
  19.    return 'assets/users/' + this.avatar;
  20.  }
  21.  onSelectUser(){
  22.    this.select.emit(this.id); //emitting the id
  23.  }
  24. }


  1. #app.component.html
  2. <app-header></app-header>
  3. <main>
  4.  <ul id="users">
  5.    <li>
  6.      <app-user [avatar]="users[0].avatar" [name]="users[0].name" [id]="users[0].id" (select)="onSelectUser($event)"/> //receiving the event and bind to the method
  7.    </li>
  8.    <li>
  9.      <app-user [avatar]="users[1].avatar" [name]="users[1].name" [id]="users[1].id" (select)="onSelectUser($event)"/>
  10.    </li>
  11.    <li>
  12.      <app-user [avatar]="users[2].avatar" [name]="users[2].name" [id]="users[2].id" (select)="onSelectUser($event)"/>
  13.    </li>
  14.    <li>
  15.      <app-user [avatar]="users[3].avatar" [name]="users[3].name" [id]="users[3].id" (select)="onSelectUser($event)"/>
  16.    </li>
  17.  </ul>
  18. </main>


  1. #app.component.ts
  2. export class AppComponent {
  3.  users = DUMMY_USERS;

  5.  onSelectUser(id:string){ //callback function called after clicking user in user component.
  6.    console.log("selected - " + id);
  7.    
  8.  }
  9. }


Alternate Method for Output

Using output (lowercase o) instead of @Output( ). In this case we dont need to explicitly create a instance of event emitter.

select = output( );

We should mention type of data we emit in select else it will throw an error during emit.

select = output<string>( );

Both @Output( ) and output( ) are same there is no difference among them.

output( ) will not create any signal it will act as only EventEmitter.

  1. #user.component.ts
  2. export class UserComponent {
  3.  @Input({required:true}) id !: string
  4.  @Input({required:true}) avatar !: string;
  5.  @Input({required:true}) name !: string;

  7.  select = output<string>(); //output method.
  8.  get imagePath(){
  9.    return 'assets/users/' + this.avatar;
  10.  }
  11.  onSelectUser(){
  12.    this.select.emit(this.id);
  13.  }
  14. } 


The reason to use this is only to avoid decorators inside component or to make code short.

We can add <string> to EventEmitter to make sure we dont emit other data type to the parent component. Its not necessary but its a good practice.

  1.  @Output() select = new EventEmitter<string>();


Now we are moving to the another component TaskComponent.

When the user is clicked the respective tasks should be displayed how to do it?

Create a component using angular cli

  1. ng g c tasks


Now once the user id is emitted from the user component and got in app component we need to send the name of that id to the tasks component.

  1. #app.component.ts
  2. import { Component } from '@angular/core';
  3. import { RouterOutlet } from '@angular/router';
  4. import { HeaderComponent } from './header/header.component';
  5. import { UserComponent } from "./user/user.component";
  6. import { DUMMY_USERS } from './dummy-users';
  7. import { TasksComponent } from "./tasks/tasks.component";

  9. @Component({
  10.  selector: 'app-root',
  11.  standalone: true,
  12.  imports: [RouterOutlet, HeaderComponent, UserComponent, TasksComponent], //TaskComponent is imported
  13.  templateUrl: './app.component.html',
  14.  styleUrl: './app.component.css'
  15. })
  16. export class AppComponent {
  17.  users = DUMMY_USERS;
  18.  selectedUserId = 'u1';

  20.  get selectedUser(){ //this is used to find the name of the id from array.
  21.    return this.users.find((user) => user.id === this.selectedUserId)!;
  22.  }

  24.  onSelectUser(id:string){
  25.    this.selectedUserId = id;
  26.    
  27.  }
  28. }


The '!' is used in like 21 to say the value will be definitely there it wont return undefined value.

  1. #app.component.html
  2. <app-tasks [name]="selectedUser.name"/>
